  "id": "019d3c6e-2297-7890-a017-bb96e36e9690",
  "content": "# Research: State of the Art in Extracting \"Why\" From Codebases (March 2026)\n\n## The Four \"Why\" Gaps\n\nWhen onboarding a repo mid-life, the hardest knowledge to extract automatically:\n1. Why decisions were made (design rationale)\n2. Business context driving the code\n3. Known technical debt and intentional shortcuts\n4. Future plans and roadmap intent\n\n## Who Is Working on This\n\n### 1. Lore Protocol (arxiv 2603.15566, March 2026)\n- Author: Ivan Stetsenko\n- Concept: \"Decision Shadow\" -- each commit captures a diff but discards the reasoning behind it\n- Solution: Git trailers (native git feature) to serialize constraints, rejected alternatives, agent directives, verification metadata into commit messages\n- Key insight: \"Rejected trailers prevent agents from re-exploring dead ends\"\n- Limitation: Only works going FORWARD. Does not retroactively recover rationale from existing repos.\n- CLI tool: `lore query` for shell-based discovery\n\n### 2. lorehq/lore (Product, 2025-2026)\n- Tagline: \"Your coding agent forgets everything between sessions. Lore fixes that.\"\n- A harness for AI coding agents: persistent memory, convention enforcement, skill capture\n- Cross-platform (Claude Code, Cursor, OpenCode)\n- Captures agent session knowledge as \"skills\" that persist\n- Limitation: Agent-centric memory, not codebase archaeology. Doesn't mine existing git history for rationale.\n\n### 3. AvraamMavridis/lore (Project, 2026)\n- \"High-context repository where AI agents read the minds of previous developers\"\n- Stores: Intent, Reasoning Trace (full chain-of-thought), Rejected Alternatives\n- Cryptographically linked to file content hashes and git commits\n- Limitation: Requires manual or agent-driven entry at write time. Not retroactive.\n\n### 4. git-why (muin-company, 2025)\n- AI-powered git history explainer\n- Uses git blame + commit messages + diffs to explain why code exists\n- Turns raw git history into human-readable narrative\n- Limitation: Quality depends on commit message quality. \"fix bug\" yields nothing.\n\n### 5. LLM Design Rationale Generation (arxiv 2504.20781, April 2025)\n- Tested 5 LLMs generating design rationale from 100 architecture problems (50 SO posts, 25 GitHub issues, 25 GitHub discussions)\n- Results: Precision 0.267-0.278, Recall 0.627-0.715, F1 0.351-0.389\n- Critical finding: 64-69% of LLM-generated arguments NOT mentioned by human experts were also rated helpful\n- Implication: LLMs over-generate but the novel arguments are mostly useful, not noise\n- Prompting: Zero-shot, CoT, and agent strategies all performed similarly\n\n### 6. CodeScene (Commercial, established)\n- Behavioral code analysis: temporal coupling, hotspot analysis, code health scores\n- Mines git history for organizational patterns (who changes what together, change frequency)\n- Quantitative signals: \"this file changes with that file 80% of the time\" = coupling\n- Limitation: Quantitative only. Detects patterns but doesn't explain rationale.\n\n### 7. Blar (Commercial, 2025-2026)\n- Codebase-aware intelligence for tech debt via PR analysis\n- 4 specialized agents (General, Debugger, Optimizer, Security)\n- Analyzed 10,000+ PRs\n- Limitation: Forward-looking (PR review), not retroactive knowledge extraction.\n\n### 8. Technical Debt Master (tdm, 2025)\n- Local LLM-powered proactive tech debt detection\n- Transforms reactive debt tracking into automated system\n- Limitation: Detects debt patterns, doesn't explain why they exist.\n\n## The Gap No One Has Filled\n\nEach tool picks ONE signal source:\n- Lore/lorehq: Agent session memory (forward only)\n- git-why: Git commit messages (retroactive but low signal)\n- CodeScene: Git behavioral patterns (quantitative, not qualitative)\n- LLM rationale paper: LLM inference from discussion context (promising recall, low precision)\n- Blar/tdm: PR/code pattern analysis (forward only)\n\nNO tool combines all four signal sources into a unified synthesis:\n1. Code structure (AST, call graph, imports) -- what corvia already has\n2. Git history (commits, blame, diffs over time) -- temporal evolution\n3. PR/issue context (descriptions, review comments, linked issues) -- human discussion\n4. LLM inference (synthesize rationale from combined signals) -- the generation step\n\n## Opportunity for Corvia\n\nCorvia is uniquely positioned because:\n- Already has code structure (adapter-git + tree-sitter + graph edges)\n- Already has a knowledge graph to store synthesized understanding\n- Already has a generation engine (RAG pipeline)\n- adapter-git could be extended to mine git history (commits, diffs, blame)\n- adapter-github (planned in D44) would bring PR/issue context\n- The synthesis pipeline would combine all signals into knowledge entries\n\nThe retroactive \"why\" extraction pipeline would be:\n1. Code structure analysis (existing) -- what connects to what\n2. Git archaeology (new) -- how the code evolved, who changed what when\n3. PR/issue mining (new, via adapter-github) -- discussions, review comments, linked issues\n4. LLM synthesis (new) -- combine all three signals to generate rationale entries\n\nThis would be the first tool to do multi-signal retroactive rationale extraction at the knowledge graph level.",
